        <p>One can observe, that with only a small number of patients available the problem is harder, such that only a small number of genes is detected. In such cases each false positive gets more weight in the calculation of the <italic>FDR </italic>and one has to expect higher <italic>FDR </italic>levels. In later interim analyses, the simulated <italic>FDR </italic>stabilizes at a more conservative level. In the setting of <italic>M </italic>= 10 interim analyses, the <italic>FDR </italic>is considerably small in the very first interim analysis. This observation can be explained by the fact that the <italic>FDR </italic>is defined to be zero when no genes are found at all.</p>
